# React Coding Style & Best Practices

> This file defines React-specific rules and best practices. It transforms common "Junior" patterns into "Pro" patterns for clean, performant, scalable, and maintainable React code.

## Mindset & Architecture

Always adopt the **Pro Mindset** instead of the Junior Mindset.

### Pro vs Junior Patterns

- **WRONG (Junior Mindset)**: Manual sync with `useEffect`, scattered state, data fetching inside `useEffect`, copy-paste logic, dependency on objects.
- **CORRECT (Pro Mindset)**: Use Derived State, Single Object State, React Query / Server Components, Custom Hooks, and primitives (or `useMemo`).

```tsx
// WRONG: Junior pattern
useEffect(() => {
  setTotal(quantity * price);
}, [quantity, price]);

// CORRECT: Pro pattern
const totalPrice = quantity * price; // Derived State
```

### Server-First Architecture

- Server Components are the **default**.
- Use Client Components (`'use client'`) **only** for interactivity, event listeners, or Browser APIs.
- Push heavy logic (data fetching, secrets) to the Server.

```tsx
// Server Component (default) - CORRECT
const data = await db.post.findMany();

// Client Component - only when needed
'use client';
function InteractiveButton() { ... }
```

## State Management

### Use Derived State Instead of Manual Sync

```tsx
// WRONG: Redundant useEffect (causes extra renders)
useEffect(() => {
  setTotal(quantity * price);
}, [quantity, price]);

// CORRECT: Derived State (single render, cleaner code)
const totalPrice = quantity * price;
```

### Prefer Single Object State (especially for Forms)

```tsx
// WRONG: Atomic state (hard to maintain)
const [firstName, setFirstName] = useState('');
const [email, setEmail] = useState('');

// CORRECT: Single Object State (scalable)
const [form, setForm] = useState({
  firstName: '',
  lastName: '',
  email: '',
  password: ''
});

const handleChange = (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
  setForm({
    ...form,
    [e.target.name]: e.target.value
  });
};
```

### Always Use Updater Functions for State Updates

```tsx
// WRONG: Relying on current state value (batching issue)
const handleAdd = () => {
  setCount(count + 1);
  setCount(count + 1); // still uses stale count
};

// CORRECT: Updater Function
const handleAdd = () => {
  setCount(prev => prev + 1);
  setCount(prev => prev + 1);
};
```

## Data Fetching

### Never Fetch Data Inside useEffect

- **WRONG**: `useEffect` + manual fetch (race conditions, stale data, extra renders).
- **CORRECT**: Use React Query / SWR **or** Server Components.

```tsx
// Server Component (Best)
const data = await db.post.findMany();

// OR with React Query (Better)
const { data, isLoading } = useQuery({ queryKey: ['posts'], queryFn: fetchPosts });
```

### Handle Race Conditions Properly

Use `AbortController` (manual) or let React Query / SWR handle deduping and cancellation automatically.

## Hooks & Performance

### Embrace Custom Hooks (DRY Principle)

```tsx
// WRONG: Copy-paste logic across components
// Component A & B both have the same window resize code

// CORRECT: Extract to Custom Hook
function useWindowSize() {
  const [size, setSize] = useState(window.innerWidth);
  // ... useEffect logic
  return size;
}
```

### Hooks Rules (Strict Order)

- Always call Hooks at the **top level** of your component.
- Never call Hooks inside conditions, loops, or early returns.

```tsx
// WRONG: Early return before all Hooks
function Component() {
  if (loading) return <Spinner />;
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0); // Hook order breaks!
  useEffect(...);
}

// CORRECT: All Hooks first
function Component() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  useEffect(...);
  if (loading) return <Spinner />;
}
```

### Avoid Reference Trap (Primitive vs Object)

```tsx
// WRONG: Object in dependency array (infinite re-renders)
useEffect(() => { ... }, [config]); // config is new object every render

// CORRECT: Use primitives or useMemo
useEffect(() => { ... }, [config.id]); // primitive
// OR
const memoConfig = useMemo(() => config, [config.id]);
```

### Avoid Stale Closures

```tsx
// WRONG: Closure captures old state
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setInterval(() => setCount(count + 1), 1000); // stale count
}, []);

// CORRECT: Updater Function
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setInterval(() => setCount(prev => prev + 1), 1000);
  return () => clearInterval(id);
}, []);
```

## TypeScript & Initialization

### Initialize State Explicitly

```tsx
// WRONG: Implicit undefined
const [user, setUser] = useState();

// CORRECT: Explicit null + generics
const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);
```

### Always Handle Loading and Optional Chaining

```tsx
// CORRECT
if (isLoading) return <Spinner />;

return <div>{user?.name}</div>;
```

## Final Pro Tips

- **React Mastery = JavaScript Mastery**: Most "weird" React bugs are actually JS Reference, Closure, or Async issues.
- Refactor one component and fix one `useEffect` today — you will immediately level up.
- Code should be **clean**, **predictable**, and **performant** by default.

Follow these rules consistently and your React code will go from Junior to Pro automatically.
